- 'Shift from a state of giving to a state of taking' refers to the transition from a positive average current to a negative average current;
- 'More than five instances of such transitions' means the battery has more than 5 data points where this transition occurs;
- 'Average change in the battery's discharged capacity' is calculated by subtracting the discharged capacity at an earlier timestamp from the discharged capacity at a later timestamp and then averaging these differences.

- Average capacity utilization is calculated as (average available energy / design capacity) * 100%;
- Average cell voltage greater than 3.5V indicates a healthy and efficient battery;
- Average maximum cell voltage delta less than 0.1V indicates stability and consistency in the battery's performance.

- 'Good' quality status indicates that the battery is functioning well and is reliable;
- 'Remaining capacity' is the battery's current charge level as a percentage of its full capacity;
- 'Discharged capacity' is the amount of charge that has been used from the battery, measured in milliampere-hours (mAh);
- 'Average power' is the mean power output of the battery, measured in watts (W).

sql:
SELECT MAX(available_energy) AS max_available_energy, 
       MIN(available_energy) AS min_available_energy
FROM available_energy;

SELECT battery_id, remaining_capacity
FROM remaining_capacity
WHERE remaining_capacity > 0.5;

external_knowledge:
- 'Higher than average energy variance' means the energy variance is above the mean energy variance of all batteries;
- 'Temperature above 20 degrees Celsius' refers to the temperature being greater than 20°C;
- 'Highest average available energy' means the battery with the greatest mean available energy.

sql:
SELECT design_capacity, actual_capacity
FROM design_capacity
WHERE capacity_variance > 0.5;

SELECT battery_id, MAX(max_cell_voltage_delta) AS max_cell_voltage_delta, MIN(max_cell_voltage_delta) AS min_cell_voltage_delta
FROM max_cell_voltage_delta
GROUP BY battery_id;

external_knowledge:
- `capacity_degradation` is calculated as \((\text{design_capacity} - \text{average_actual_capacity}) / \text{design_capacity} \times 100\);
- `voltage_degradation` is calculated as \((\text{average_actual_voltage} - \text{nominal_voltage}) / \text{nominal_voltage} \times 100\);
- `total_lost_capacity` is calculated as \(\text{average_actual_capacity} - (\text{average_remaining_capacity} / 100) \times \text{average_actual_capacity}\);
- `quality_status` of 'good' indicates that the battery meets the quality standards.

sql:
SELECT timestamp, max_cell_voltage_delta
FROM max_cell_voltage_delta
WHERE max_cell_voltage_delta = (
    SELECT MAX(max_cell_voltage_delta)
    FROM max_cell_voltage_delta
);

SELECT serial_number, design_capacity
FROM batteries
ORDER BY design_capacity DESC;

